		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span class="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=292031"><span id=Scholar>ubermuse</span></a><b><span id=Scholar><br>Scholar</span></b><br />34 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span class="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=ubermuse&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>I'm at lvl 48 and need new gear badly. I am not in a guild, and finding grps for LDoN adventures is a hit or miss affair so I haven't been able to accumulate many adv points to buy LDoN gear. I have saved up a bit of plat however, andhave been browsing gear in the bazaar. So far I have noticed 3 schools of thought on whats important at higher levels. One is gear with lots of mana and hp to convert into mana. The second is int/mana gear to creat the largest mana pool possible. The third is too get gear with focus effect on it above all else. I can understand how spell haste would be a great thing to have, as the higher level spells have a long cast time, and regeant conservation would mitigate the need for mega mana, but are they worth more than int/mana gear? Is there really a benefit to one school of thought over the others?</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td><td align="right" id="fs8" >13 Replies</td></tr></table>
